The Comparator interface in Java is used to define custom sorting logic for objects. It belongs to java.util package allows sorting of objects of user-defined classes without modifying their source code. It is especially useful when:
‚ÄĘ We need multiple sorting strategies for a class.
‚ÄĘ We want to keep sorting logic separate from the class definition.
‚ÄĘ Comparator is a functional interface as it contains only one abstract method compare().

-> Syntax
class MyComparator implements Comparator<Type> {
           public int compare(Type obj1, Type obj2) {
               // comparison logic
      }
}

‚ÄĘ Returns negative integer if obj1 < obj2.
‚ÄĘ Returns 0 if obj1 == obj2.
‚ÄĘ Returns positive integer if obj1 > obj2.

